Explanation:

I examined controllers/orderController.js and routes/orderRoutes.js to determine what responses the PUT /api/orders/{id}/deliver endpoint produces.

- Route protection and role: The route is defined as router.route('/:id/deliver').put(protect, admin, updateOrderToDelivered). The protect middleware returns 401 errors when authentication fails; the admin middleware returns 401 when the user is not an admin. So 401 Unauthorized responses are possible.
- Successful response: In updateOrderToDelivered, when the order is found, it sets order.isDelivered = true, order.deliveredAt = Date.now(), saves the order and responds with the saved order object (res.json(updatedOrder)). Therefore a 200 response returns the full Order object.
- Not found: If the order is not found, the controller sets res.status(404) and throws "Order not found", so a 404 response with an error message is possible.
- Other errors: The appâ€™s error middleware will turn uncaught exceptions into a JSON error response; include a general 500 response for server errors.

I used the order model (models/orderModel.js) to derive the structure of the Order object returned on success. I did not use $ref; all schemas are inlined. The error responses use a simple JSON object with a "message" string field, matching how the error middleware formats error responses.

